1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:26,000
Today is Wednesday, March 13, 2013. My name is John Dittmer and I am here in Tchula, Mississippi with videographer John Bishop to interview Mrs. Julia Matilda Burns, a leading civil rights activist in a Holmes County movement.

3
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:34,000
This interview will become part of the Smithsonian's National Museum of African American History and Culture in Washington, D.C.

4
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:40,000
As Burns were delighted to be here today and we thank you for taking the time to talk with us.

5
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:44,000
Thank you very much. I hope I can give some service to you all.

6
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:50,000
We would like to start by talking about where you were born and raised in your family.

7
00:00:50,000 --> 00:01:04,000
I was born and raised in Greenwood, Mississippi. In the family we have one brother and three sisters, mother Margaret Griffin, father Trevenu Griffin.

8
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:08,000
By the age of three we moved to Humphreys County.

9
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:10,000
What did you do there?

10
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:22,000
Well, at that time in the early forties the government was purchasing land to yield people their own home.

11
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:28,000
So my father took advantage of that situation because we were living in the city of Greenwood on the streets of the same.

12
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:32,000
No place to play or nothing like that. So he decided that we all go to the country.

13
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:40,000
So we moved to Humphreys County and on that set up we bought a government plot.

14
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:43,000
the Farm Security Administration (FSA). Right, the Farm Security Administration (FSA).

15
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:50,000
In any way we got, I think it was 123 acres of land to farm and etc.

16
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:56,000
And that gave us a stepping stone to progress.

17
00:01:56,000 --> 00:01:58,000
What is your father's life cotton?

18
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:08,000
We had cotton, corn, can, truck patch and we had chicken, hogs, cows, guinnies, ducks and everything.

19
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:10,000
You got names.

20
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:12,000
Four forests.

21
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:18,000
Right. I had all the never-never land. I guess you call it.

22
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:20,000
Well, I had to come out of the camp.

23
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:23,000
Three boys, one boy and three girls.

24
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:27,000
I'm the second one on the list.

25
00:02:27,000 --> 00:02:31,000
My brother's older than I. He's in Buffalo now.

26
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:35,000
But I have a sister still on the home place in civil setting.

27
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:39,000
And I have a sister in Chicago and one in Oak Park, Michigan.

28
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:43,000
We've only two here in Mississippi. Here by this left.

29
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:45,000
Right, they did. They left.

30
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:51,000
My brother left earlier than anyone because he wanted to help me go to college.

31
00:02:51,000 --> 00:02:55,000
I finished high school and he decided that he was going to help me go to college.

32
00:02:55,000 --> 00:02:59,000
My father thought it would be best for me to stay and get an education.

33
00:02:59,000 --> 00:03:03,000
So he went to New York and got a job with John Motors.

34
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:07,000
And that's how I got my education.

35
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:11,000
He would work and send money back home and help me get an education.

36
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:15,000
Who went up on the farm? Did you get all the kids' pitch-in?

37
00:03:15,000 --> 00:03:17,000
Everybody had to pitch in.

38
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:21,000
Unfortunately, my mother passed when I was only 13 years old.

39
00:03:21,000 --> 00:03:27,000
So I had to shift position early in life, become the head of the household as a female.

40
00:03:27,000 --> 00:03:31,000
And my sisters and brothers continued to work on the farm.

41
00:03:31,000 --> 00:03:36,000
But I was mostly part farmer and part housekeeper.

42
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:39,000
Hepp and all of us get together.

43
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:41,000
So you got to grow up overnight?

44
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:43,000
I grew up overnight.

45
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:51,000
So what about your school and your what you were at moved out of Greenwood before you were in the first grade?

46
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:53,000
Right.

47
00:03:53,000 --> 00:03:57,000
Moved out of Greenwood by the age of four.

48
00:03:57,000 --> 00:03:59,000
In fact, I remember correctly.

49
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:01,000
But my brother was six.

50
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:07,000
And we moved into the Humphreys County area near school.

51
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:11,000
And my brother was a kind of person that he would always pick on.

52
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:14,000
So my mother was a teacher.

53
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:21,000
So to keep her from being in the middle of the children's fight, I went to school too.

54
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:23,000
So I wasn't one who was fighting from her brother.

55
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:27,000
He was start to fight, but he couldn't do nothing with him.

56
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:31,000
So I had to fight the big boys off of him.

57
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:33,000
So that made me get a start in school earlier.

58
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:35,000
So I started to school.

59
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:37,000
And I was at about four and a half years old.

60
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:39,000
And I made a fight.

61
00:04:39,000 --> 00:04:43,000
And at home with my mother, you know, naturally she's going to teach us how to read and write.

62
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:45,000
I was able to do my reading and writing.

63
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:48,000
And then I got the little do-fund, the little paper bag book.

64
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:51,000
Find another do-fund, a little bit harder.

65
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:53,000
And find a hot bag book in one year.

66
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:55,000
And so many worries.

67
00:04:55,000 --> 00:04:58,000
And that time it was considered a third grade.

68
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:00,000
So that's the way I moved on up.

69
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:02,000
And eventually called up with my brother.

70
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:04,000
He was ahead of me, two years ahead of me.

71
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:06,000
But I eventually called up with him.

72
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:10,000
And we went on through grandma school and high school together.

73
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:11,000
And he was not much over.

74
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:13,000
Two years older than I.

75
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:14,000
He skipped two years.

76
00:05:14,000 --> 00:05:15,000
He skipped two, made two years in one.

77
00:05:15,000 --> 00:05:16,000
Tell us about the school.

78
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:21,000
During that time it was, it wasn't a plantation school, but it was old.

79
00:05:21,000 --> 00:05:24,000
It wasn't an old building either, but it was an old time.

80
00:05:24,000 --> 00:05:29,000
It because they had the pot bellest stone to heat.

81
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:33,000
Children had to get wood to start to find, keep warm with everything.

82
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:39,000
At that time there was two teachers, two teachers in the whole big room,

83
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:42,000
from one through eight.

84
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:46,000
So how did that operate during the day?

85
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:49,000
During that time it was marvelous.

86
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:52,000
Because the two teachers was, I guess you would call it now,

87
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:53,000
or teacher in a principal.

88
00:05:53,000 --> 00:05:56,000
Because the eight grade person was the overseer.

89
00:05:56,000 --> 00:05:58,000
It went well.

90
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:00,000
And you learned from the classes ahead of you two.

91
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:01,000
Yes, I did.

92
00:06:01,000 --> 00:06:03,000
Because a big open setting.

93
00:06:03,000 --> 00:06:08,000
The upper brain was always more interested.

94
00:06:08,000 --> 00:06:11,000
You can hear everybody's in the classroom, you know.

95
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:14,000
Paying attention, you could know what the other people were doing.

96
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:16,000
There was no advantages to what happened.

97
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:17,000
It was.

98
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:20,000
And in a way we made it well through that situation.

99
00:06:20,000 --> 00:06:28,000
And after, I guess, probably three years, they consolidated the schools.

100
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:33,000
And the teachers never going to, the lower part of Humphreys County's county,

101
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:37,000
as compared to us in the center part of Humphreys County County, came together.

102
00:06:37,000 --> 00:06:44,000
And they named the school, Humphreys County, now they named the school, Womack and Hodge.

103
00:06:44,000 --> 00:06:49,000
The Hodges were down on the lower end of the county.

104
00:06:49,000 --> 00:06:52,000
And the Womack was in the middle of the county.

105
00:06:52,000 --> 00:06:55,000
So we went to, the school then became Womack and Hodge.

106
00:06:55,000 --> 00:06:58,000
We stayed there until after graduation.

107
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:02,000
I guess seventh grade, then they built a new school.

108
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:05,000
And they called it the Womack High School, too.

109
00:07:05,000 --> 00:07:08,000
And that school went until eight grade.

110
00:07:08,000 --> 00:07:11,000
After eight grade we went to Louise to Humphreys County County.

111
00:07:11,000 --> 00:07:15,000
The still in Humphreys County County, Humphreys County County Training School in Louise Mississippi.

112
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:19,000
Now, what did you enter, what year did you enter the Louise School?

113
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:26,000
It must have been in 50, 50, 50, 51.

114
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:30,000
And there was nine grades.

115
00:07:30,000 --> 00:07:38,000
Stay there until 54, after 54, finishing high school,

116
00:07:38,000 --> 00:07:42,000
I went to Mississippi Valley State University.

117
00:07:42,000 --> 00:07:44,000
I went about a little later.

118
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:47,000
54 was also the year of the Brown decision.

119
00:07:47,000 --> 00:07:50,000
Not at that time, not at that time.

120
00:07:50,000 --> 00:07:55,000
You know, it probably was in the new, but you know how you thought at that time.

121
00:07:55,000 --> 00:07:57,000
News is news.

122
00:07:57,000 --> 00:08:02,000
And if it doesn't affect anyone, you know it doesn't register with you.

123
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:07,000
But later on in life, I realized what was going on with Brown v. Board of Education.

124
00:08:07,000 --> 00:08:09,000
Of course, nothing happened in Mississippi anyway.

125
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:13,000
No, no, no, no. That was in Kansas City, so that bypassed us quite a bit.

126
00:08:13,000 --> 00:08:23,000
One of the things that the state of Mississippi tried to do anticipating Brown was to beef up the black schools

127
00:08:23,000 --> 00:08:27,000
so that they could say we're separate, but we're equal.

128
00:08:27,000 --> 00:08:29,000
Did you see any of that?

129
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:34,000
Anything coming into your school that's like new buildings or materials or anything?

130
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:36,000
None whatsoever.

131
00:08:36,000 --> 00:08:37,000
None whatsoever.

132
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:38,000
Not at all.

133
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:39,000
Not at all.

134
00:08:39,000 --> 00:08:40,000
Not even textbooks.

135
00:08:40,000 --> 00:08:41,000
Yeah.

136
00:08:41,000 --> 00:08:43,000
What about textbooks?

137
00:08:43,000 --> 00:08:44,000
Textbooks.

138
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:51,000
Now, in my ninth grade year in Humphreys County Training School, I saw new textbooks

139
00:08:51,000 --> 00:08:55,000
because they introduced a class that was called Everyday Science.

140
00:08:55,000 --> 00:08:58,000
And there were no everyday science before then.

141
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:03,000
So once they introduced that everyday science in the Humphreys County School District,

142
00:09:03,000 --> 00:09:05,000
that afforded us to have new books.

143
00:09:05,000 --> 00:09:08,000
The first time seeing a new book was in my ninth grade year.

144
00:09:08,000 --> 00:09:16,000
And the rest were passed down from the high school.

145
00:09:16,000 --> 00:09:19,000
So I lost my train as well here.

146
00:09:19,000 --> 00:09:24,000
But you were...

147
00:09:24,000 --> 00:09:30,000
Well, let me just go with this because it was time here in the 1950s.

148
00:09:30,000 --> 00:09:34,000
And there is racial violence going on.

149
00:09:34,000 --> 00:09:41,000
And asking everybody about the Emmett Till case and what you remember about it.

150
00:09:41,000 --> 00:09:43,000
Recalling the Emmett Till case.

151
00:09:43,000 --> 00:09:45,000
I'm not good at the date now.

152
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:53,000
But anyway, 55, 55, I was finishing high school that year.

153
00:09:53,000 --> 00:09:57,000
We used to get, we'll call it a jet magazine, still in publication.

154
00:09:57,000 --> 00:10:02,000
And that's why I saw and was able to read the story on the Emmett Till situation.

155
00:10:02,000 --> 00:10:04,000
And then the high school jet first.

156
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:06,000
No, no, it came to my home.

157
00:10:06,000 --> 00:10:08,000
Yeah, because I think they mean loudness.

158
00:10:08,000 --> 00:10:10,000
No, he got it in home.

159
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:14,000
My mother and father were kind of people who thought we need to keep with newspapers and stuff like that.

160
00:10:14,000 --> 00:10:16,000
And we did get them.

161
00:10:16,000 --> 00:10:22,000
And that was the magazine that we all raised to read because we could read about what other black people were doing.

162
00:10:22,000 --> 00:10:24,000
That's when I remember what was going on with him.

163
00:10:24,000 --> 00:10:26,000
That's how I recall him.

164
00:10:26,000 --> 00:10:32,000
I remember the picture of the body, which was terrible.

165
00:10:32,000 --> 00:10:35,000
I just couldn't believe it, but it was true.

166
00:10:35,000 --> 00:10:39,000
Do you remember any kind of discussion in the family or with your friends about this?

167
00:10:39,000 --> 00:10:44,000
Because he was not much, quite a little bit younger than you.

168
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:50,000
Well, my brother, my father always tell him, be careful.

169
00:10:50,000 --> 00:10:52,000
Don't bother them, white girls.

170
00:10:52,000 --> 00:10:54,000
Don't play with the white girls.

171
00:10:54,000 --> 00:11:00,000
Even though they were known in our community, even the boys go everywhere, so to say.

172
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:03,000
And he had access to the family vehicle, so he was moving around.

173
00:11:03,000 --> 00:11:08,000
And my dad would always tell him not to whistle, let them not to play with them, you know, just ignore them.

174
00:11:08,000 --> 00:11:13,000
But now, believe it or not, there were some black boys in Belzoni, the situation.

175
00:11:13,000 --> 00:11:15,000
It's Belzoni that's sitting down.

176
00:11:15,000 --> 00:11:18,000
They had white girlfriends at that time.

177
00:11:18,000 --> 00:11:20,000
And nothing was done about it.

178
00:11:20,000 --> 00:11:21,000
People would see them.

179
00:11:21,000 --> 00:11:23,000
They were walking together, riding together, and etc.

180
00:11:23,000 --> 00:11:26,000
Nobody paid an attention to it.

181
00:11:26,000 --> 00:11:31,000
But no one wanted to be falling in the footsteps of Emmett Till.

182
00:11:31,000 --> 00:11:39,000
The trial was held, and the people were set free.

183
00:11:39,000 --> 00:11:44,000
And things sort of took off from there in terms of...

184
00:11:44,000 --> 00:11:52,000
I was telling Ms. Head that a number of civil rights activists, you know, sort of pointed to the Emmett Till case.

185
00:11:52,000 --> 00:11:59,000
Attorney Boyd and their lives, from that point on, they realized something had to be done, because that could have been them.

186
00:11:59,000 --> 00:12:01,000
Yes, that was a serious time in our lives.

187
00:12:01,000 --> 00:12:04,000
When you look back at...

188
00:12:04,000 --> 00:12:07,000
No one wants to repeat that situation.

189
00:12:07,000 --> 00:12:17,000
And they had the film set up and everything, and she'll divide it, and that picture came through in the jet magazine, and it was just a horrible sight to see.

190
00:12:18,000 --> 00:12:21,000
What talk about another institution in the air community of the church?

191
00:12:21,000 --> 00:12:22,000
Was that important to you?

192
00:12:22,000 --> 00:12:24,000
Extremely important to us.

193
00:12:24,000 --> 00:12:29,000
Believe it or not, we grew up between a Baptist church and a Methodist church.

194
00:12:29,000 --> 00:12:32,000
There was a sanctified church further down.

195
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:36,000
So every Sunday morning, we had to be in one.

196
00:12:36,000 --> 00:12:38,000
The Baptist of the Methodist.

197
00:12:38,000 --> 00:12:41,000
We didn't have a...

198
00:12:41,000 --> 00:12:44,000
I don't know where we had a church. We just had to go.

199
00:12:44,000 --> 00:12:51,000
But the Baptist church was closer to us than the Methodist church.

200
00:12:51,000 --> 00:12:56,000
We could actually walk to the Baptist church, even though we were Methodist by faith.

201
00:12:56,000 --> 00:12:59,000
And we would go every Sunday morning.

202
00:12:59,000 --> 00:13:02,000
Our pastor, he was the fourth Sunday in the month.

203
00:13:02,000 --> 00:13:07,000
The fourth Sunday in the month, there would let us use the truck to go to our church.

204
00:13:07,000 --> 00:13:11,000
But anyway, we stayed with the Methodist church, but we just attended the Baptist church.

205
00:13:11,000 --> 00:13:16,000
If something special was going on in the sanctified church, we would call it.

206
00:13:16,000 --> 00:13:19,000
We were right to see that, but some of our friends would have to pick us up

207
00:13:19,000 --> 00:13:22,000
because it was further down the road than our church.

208
00:13:22,000 --> 00:13:25,000
So religiously, we had to be involved.

209
00:13:25,000 --> 00:13:26,000
You were family of faith.

210
00:13:26,000 --> 00:13:32,000
Right. We were always in one church or the other, every Sunday.

211
00:13:32,000 --> 00:13:35,000
Then we still...

212
00:13:35,000 --> 00:13:37,000
I'm still Methodist.

213
00:13:37,000 --> 00:13:39,000
You didn't make your Jewish.

214
00:13:39,000 --> 00:13:41,000
I made my choice.

215
00:13:41,000 --> 00:13:48,000
What were the major influences on you when you were growing up?

216
00:13:48,000 --> 00:13:56,000
My major influence that I could recall was my 10th grade English teacher.

217
00:13:56,000 --> 00:13:58,000
Very smart lady.

218
00:13:58,000 --> 00:13:59,000
Very smart.

219
00:13:59,000 --> 00:14:05,000
And she just had a liking for people who wanted to do something.

220
00:14:05,000 --> 00:14:08,000
I guess she could see in me what I could not see in myself.

221
00:14:08,000 --> 00:14:13,000
And she suggested to me that I should go to college in major English.

222
00:14:13,000 --> 00:14:15,000
And that's what I did.

223
00:14:15,000 --> 00:14:20,000
And I think about her continuously now, you know, what an impact that was on my life, you know.

224
00:14:20,000 --> 00:14:24,000
You know, 10th grade children don't think about their future.

225
00:14:24,000 --> 00:14:27,000
You know, they're just having a good time.

226
00:14:27,000 --> 00:14:31,000
And by them, you know, during that time, in the back of...

227
00:14:31,000 --> 00:14:37,000
During that time, teachers took an interest in children where they are being in their future.

228
00:14:37,000 --> 00:14:43,000
All the way through high school, there was some teacher telling you what you ought to do, what you should do.

229
00:14:43,000 --> 00:14:48,000
And those teachers even visited the families in the community and told the parents,

230
00:14:48,000 --> 00:14:56,000
your child did this, your child did that, and believe it not, you know, if it's good, the parent will work with it if not the parent will try to correct it.

231
00:14:57,000 --> 00:15:00,000
So she told me that I should become an English teacher.

232
00:15:00,000 --> 00:15:02,000
And I worked toward that end.

233
00:15:02,000 --> 00:15:05,000
And I went home and I told my "Daddy, I said, Dad, miss...

234
00:15:05,000 --> 00:15:09,000
She said, I'm going to first name, so I need to go to school to become an English teacher.

235
00:15:09,000 --> 00:15:11,000
He said, you want to teach English?

236
00:15:11,000 --> 00:15:13,000
I said, she said, I want to be pretty good at it.

237
00:15:13,000 --> 00:15:15,000
And that's what I decided to do.

238
00:15:15,000 --> 00:15:18,000
And he said, okay, well, I do what I can to help you.

239
00:15:18,000 --> 00:15:19,000
I finished school at the year.

240
00:15:19,000 --> 00:15:25,000
My brother went off to work and my father and I went through the educational process.

241
00:15:26,000 --> 00:15:28,000
And we were about three miles from the bus stop.

242
00:15:28,000 --> 00:15:30,000
I rode the bus to college.

243
00:15:30,000 --> 00:15:34,000
We didn't have enough money to stay on campus, so I rode the bus.

244
00:15:34,000 --> 00:15:39,000
So you were the only one of your siblings to go to college then?

245
00:15:39,000 --> 00:15:40,000
At that time, yes.

246
00:15:40,000 --> 00:15:41,000
At that time, yes.

247
00:15:41,000 --> 00:15:45,000
And laid on my sister next to me, went on, but she had gone to Chicago.

248
00:15:45,000 --> 00:15:47,000
She went to Malcolm X College.

249
00:15:47,000 --> 00:15:48,000
The Malcolm X College College?

250
00:15:48,000 --> 00:15:50,000
Okay, she went there.

251
00:15:51,000 --> 00:15:56,000
As a former 10th grade English teacher, I'm interested in what the school class was like.

252
00:15:56,000 --> 00:15:57,000
What books did you read?

253
00:15:57,000 --> 00:16:00,000
Did you have access to libraries?

254
00:16:00,000 --> 00:16:05,000
We had access to library books.

255
00:16:05,000 --> 00:16:08,000
And we could check them out and take them home with us.

256
00:16:08,000 --> 00:16:12,000
But not like now, you know, the children cannot take them away from the school.

257
00:16:12,000 --> 00:16:14,000
They have to study them in the school.

258
00:16:14,000 --> 00:16:19,000
We could take them home and keep them with the week or so, whatever you were doing with either returning home.

259
00:16:19,000 --> 00:16:23,000
You know, with either returning home and you know, you used the book to your advantage.

260
00:16:23,000 --> 00:16:25,000
What did you remember reading?

261
00:16:25,000 --> 00:16:27,000
Oh my goodness.

262
00:16:27,000 --> 00:16:29,000
Way back then.

263
00:16:29,000 --> 00:16:32,000
I was crazy about Alfred Lord Tennyson.

264
00:16:32,000 --> 00:16:39,000
He was a good poet and I would just sit and read for days, some of his poems.

265
00:16:39,000 --> 00:16:42,000
And that inspired me too, too.

266
00:16:42,000 --> 00:16:44,000
That was another one.

267
00:16:44,000 --> 00:16:45,000
I can't think of it.

268
00:16:45,000 --> 00:16:47,000
It got a poem was one.

269
00:16:47,000 --> 00:16:49,000
I guess that was another one.

270
00:16:49,000 --> 00:16:52,000
But I just like the reason because they were in tune to nature.

271
00:16:52,000 --> 00:16:56,000
I like nature and the activities that's there.

272
00:16:56,000 --> 00:16:59,000
Did you read any black writers that you read?

273
00:16:59,000 --> 00:17:01,000
I mean Richard Wright on the screen.

274
00:17:01,000 --> 00:17:02,000
Oh yes.

275
00:17:02,000 --> 00:17:05,000
But I read his book, Soul On Ice and I got made.

276
00:17:05,000 --> 00:17:09,000
It's Soul on Ice.

277
00:17:09,000 --> 00:17:11,000
I said, Violet.

278
00:17:11,000 --> 00:17:12,000
You ever said Eldridge Cleaver?

279
00:17:12,000 --> 00:17:13,000
Right, right.

280
00:17:13,000 --> 00:17:14,000
That's right.

281
00:17:14,000 --> 00:17:15,000
You ever said Eldridge Cleaver?

282
00:17:15,000 --> 00:17:16,000
No, right.

283
00:17:16,000 --> 00:17:21,000
I didn't get a chance to, I didn't like that too well.

284
00:17:21,000 --> 00:17:28,000
I guess it reminded me so much of what I had heard about a little wealthy, you know.

285
00:17:28,000 --> 00:17:31,000
So talk about it.

286
00:17:31,000 --> 00:17:34,000
Now Mississippi Valley, as I recall, was a new school.

287
00:17:34,000 --> 00:17:39,000
Mississippi Valley was built in 1950.

288
00:17:39,000 --> 00:17:41,000
I think that's when they had the first class.

289
00:17:41,000 --> 00:17:45,000
I think I had two buildings or three buildings.

290
00:17:45,000 --> 00:17:47,000
What many buildings there?

291
00:17:47,000 --> 00:17:54,000
But they had an administration building and a classroom building and something else at that time.

292
00:17:54,000 --> 00:18:02,000
I went to school there through the, I guess you call it, classroom building.

293
00:18:02,000 --> 00:18:04,000
Everything was in one building.

294
00:18:04,000 --> 00:18:07,000
All of the majors were operated from one building.

295
00:18:07,000 --> 00:18:11,000
We didn't have access to the whole, you know, building like they have now.

296
00:18:11,000 --> 00:18:13,000
So everything took place in one building.

297
00:18:13,000 --> 00:18:14,000
How many students were there?

298
00:18:14,000 --> 00:18:17,000
I don't recall.

299
00:18:17,000 --> 00:18:30,000
It wasn't that many because the class that graduated in 152, 1816, it was 16 or 32 between the two, 16 or 32 students.

300
00:18:30,000 --> 00:18:31,000
And that was it.

301
00:18:31,000 --> 00:18:37,000
Small student body at that time, but it has grown quite a bit now.

302
00:18:37,000 --> 00:18:39,000
Different majors.

303
00:18:39,000 --> 00:18:43,000
How many majors were there at the beginning of us that started out small?

304
00:18:43,000 --> 00:18:46,000
I think they were predominantly education.

305
00:18:46,000 --> 00:18:53,000
It was designed to give people a chance to major in education.

306
00:18:53,000 --> 00:19:01,000
President Dr. White, James Herbert White, came with the idea that they needed teachers in the Delta.

307
00:19:01,000 --> 00:19:04,000
And he came out of Tennessee, I'm for gun, we're part.

308
00:19:04,000 --> 00:19:12,000
Now, came out of Tennessee and this was his goal to create opportunities for teachers to be developed in the Delta area.

309
00:19:13,000 --> 00:19:15,000
Can someone graduate?

310
00:19:15,000 --> 00:19:18,000
I graduated in 55.

311
00:19:18,000 --> 00:19:20,000
59, 59, 59.

312
00:19:20,000 --> 00:19:23,000
Did you have any new student teaching as part of this?

313
00:19:23,000 --> 00:19:24,000
We had to do student teaching.

314
00:19:24,000 --> 00:19:26,000
That was a requirement at the time.

315
00:19:26,000 --> 00:19:32,000
We had to do student teaching and the student teaching would come out and observe you and all like that.

316
00:19:32,000 --> 00:19:33,000
What did you do?

317
00:19:33,000 --> 00:19:37,000
I did my in Belzoni, where I grew up in Humphreys County.

318
00:19:37,000 --> 00:19:40,000
It was a building that was made in high school at the time.

319
00:19:40,000 --> 00:19:42,000
It was made in high school in Belzoni.

320
00:19:42,000 --> 00:19:47,000
What was the high school life at something that we don't hear very much about?

321
00:19:47,000 --> 00:19:51,000
The school life in the 1950s at the end of the segregated era.

322
00:19:51,000 --> 00:19:58,000
The school life for me, I guess it took a turn for exploring.

323
00:19:58,000 --> 00:20:06,000
It was a time where I was really trying to find out what is going on and why is going on along with trying to get a decent education.

324
00:20:07,000 --> 00:20:11,000
When you were student teaching, what were your students?

325
00:20:11,000 --> 00:20:15,000
Did they have aspirations to go to college or what were they?

326
00:20:15,000 --> 00:20:22,000
I had some very good students as a student teacher because I don't know where you heard of Clare Ried and Bells on it.

327
00:20:22,000 --> 00:20:24,000
That was one of my students.

328
00:20:24,000 --> 00:20:28,000
But then I had some on the flip side all together different from her.

329
00:20:28,000 --> 00:20:33,000
Clare Ried and Cara Harris and Selvam Mohu turned out to be very productive people.

330
00:20:34,000 --> 00:20:37,000
I remember them. I see them. I ask about them.

331
00:20:37,000 --> 00:20:41,000
Some of them are doing well and some of them are not.

332
00:20:41,000 --> 00:20:43,000
Aspirations for them.

333
00:20:43,000 --> 00:20:47,000
It was kind of so, so, so, so.

334
00:20:47,000 --> 00:20:50,000
And then you got your first teaching job?

335
00:20:50,000 --> 00:20:52,000
I got my first teaching job there.

336
00:20:52,000 --> 00:20:54,000
But I wasn't married at the time.

337
00:20:54,000 --> 00:20:59,000
After being there for a while, I got married in my second year there.

338
00:20:59,000 --> 00:21:01,000
Then I went to Chicago.

339
00:21:02,000 --> 00:21:04,000
I didn't do anything in Chicago.

340
00:21:04,000 --> 00:21:07,000
The Chicago was not the place for me. That's why I'm here now.

341
00:21:07,000 --> 00:21:10,000
The Mississippi wasn't the place for me.

342
00:21:10,000 --> 00:21:13,000
Mississippi went to Chicago.

343
00:21:13,000 --> 00:21:20,000
But the one I was there was so cold it must have been in 50 or 60.

344
00:21:20,000 --> 00:21:25,000
61, 60 or 61, 60, 59 and 60.

345
00:21:25,000 --> 00:21:28,000
It was so cold in Chicago, I didn't even open the front door.

346
00:21:29,000 --> 00:21:33,000
My husband would come through the back door to keep the cold air from coming through the front door.

347
00:21:33,000 --> 00:21:35,000
So I stayed there that year and I said,

348
00:21:35,000 --> 00:21:36,000
What were you doing?

349
00:21:36,000 --> 00:21:37,000
He was working there.

350
00:21:37,000 --> 00:21:38,000
He was working there.

351
00:21:38,000 --> 00:21:41,000
Working at a couple of places called We Boat.

352
00:21:41,000 --> 00:21:44,000
We Boat in Chicago? Big department, still.

353
00:21:44,000 --> 00:21:46,000
He was a salesperson, not in there.

354
00:21:46,000 --> 00:21:48,000
But I just couldn't take that cold weather.

355
00:21:48,000 --> 00:21:52,000
So I stayed in and I promised myself when the weather changed, I'm going home.

356
00:21:52,000 --> 00:21:55,000
I told him I was going home but he said, no, I got to work.

357
00:21:55,000 --> 00:21:56,000
I got to work.

358
00:21:56,000 --> 00:22:01,000
So I kept fussing about him going home and going home and we finally came home.

359
00:22:01,000 --> 00:22:03,000
And he came home and he started farming.

360
00:22:03,000 --> 00:22:05,000
And that's how we got back here.

361
00:22:05,000 --> 00:22:08,000
Maybe it was your family farm?

362
00:22:08,000 --> 00:22:10,000
No, he had a farm here.

363
00:22:10,000 --> 00:22:14,000
His family had a farm just like my family had a farm.

364
00:22:14,000 --> 00:22:18,000
Same process through the farm and home administration.

365
00:22:18,000 --> 00:22:20,000
So you were independent then?

366
00:22:20,000 --> 00:22:23,000
White people in terms economically.

367
00:22:23,000 --> 00:22:30,000
Well, we didn't share crop but we had to go to the the Farm Security Administration (FSA) for loans.

368
00:22:30,000 --> 00:22:33,000
And they created the problem, you know.

369
00:22:33,000 --> 00:22:35,000
But we made it pretty good.

370
00:22:35,000 --> 00:22:38,000
I remember one year my father made one bale of cotton.

371
00:22:38,000 --> 00:22:40,000
one bale of cotton.

372
00:22:40,000 --> 00:22:45,000
Everybody laughed at him and saw him feel sorry for him as to how he was going to take care of family.

373
00:22:45,000 --> 00:22:47,000
Well, one bale of cotton.

374
00:22:47,000 --> 00:22:50,000
We had cows, holes and everything else, you know.

375
00:22:50,000 --> 00:22:59,000
We only had to buy sugar and flour because there was a man with a grits meal in the community ground, a corner for meals and grits.

376
00:22:59,000 --> 00:23:00,000
So we made it.

377
00:23:00,000 --> 00:23:07,000
And with the auction and all of that, we had, we worked but we had to be some living, didn't have any money though.

378
00:23:07,000 --> 00:23:10,000
Did you have much contact with Warts?

379
00:23:10,000 --> 00:23:11,000
No.

380
00:23:11,000 --> 00:23:13,000
We would see them passing by.

381
00:23:13,000 --> 00:23:17,000
But now there were two merchants in the area.

382
00:23:17,000 --> 00:23:21,000
There was a merchant in Belzoni, there was a merchant in Cardis.

383
00:23:21,000 --> 00:23:26,000
My father would trust us to go there to get what we needed.

384
00:23:26,000 --> 00:23:30,000
And the next day we needed meat or something like that of sugar.

385
00:23:30,000 --> 00:23:35,000
He made provision for us to go there and get what we needed like that.

386
00:23:35,000 --> 00:23:37,000
I heard Belzoni was pretty tough, too.

387
00:23:37,000 --> 00:23:38,000
It was.

388
00:23:38,000 --> 00:23:39,000
It was.

389
00:23:40,000 --> 00:23:44,000
Belzoni now is, I don't think it's bad now.

390
00:23:44,000 --> 00:23:45,000
You're back at the time.

391
00:23:45,000 --> 00:23:46,000
You're back at the time.

392
00:23:46,000 --> 00:23:52,000
At the time it was, people were really afraid to go to Belzoni.

393
00:23:52,000 --> 00:23:55,000
They were lier than one, on when they were afraid.

394
00:23:55,000 --> 00:23:57,000
Now they were lier than one of Belzoni.

395
00:23:57,000 --> 00:24:02,000
And once you got in there, you picked up your items and hurried out of Belzoni.

396
00:24:02,000 --> 00:24:07,000
There were a family of boys down below us, the Buckston boys.

397
00:24:07,000 --> 00:24:10,000
They had to go to town every Saturday night, so to say them.

398
00:24:10,000 --> 00:24:13,000
And it was always a problem with those boys.

399
00:24:13,000 --> 00:24:16,000
Because the father had to go back there Sunday morning and get them out of jail.

400
00:24:16,000 --> 00:24:18,000
But we didn't experience that.

401
00:24:18,000 --> 00:24:20,000
We knew where to stay at home.

402
00:24:20,000 --> 00:24:23,000
I mentioned this because among civil rights workers,

403
00:24:23,000 --> 00:24:26,000
Belzoni was known as a really tough town.

404
00:24:26,000 --> 00:24:30,000
And when they were having a debate about bringing in the freedom of summer volunteers,

405
00:24:30,000 --> 00:24:35,000
they said, well, we're going to bring white style to sort of cause trouble.

406
00:24:35,000 --> 00:24:42,000
And one woman person said, well, let's bring a thousand of them put them all in the same way.

407
00:24:42,000 --> 00:24:46,000
Belzoni could not have hold of a thousand.

408
00:24:46,000 --> 00:24:48,000
So, yeah, another.

409
00:24:48,000 --> 00:24:53,000
And then after you came back from Chicago, why, what did you do?

410
00:24:53,000 --> 00:24:58,000
After I came from Chicago, there was a principal by the name of SB Marshall.

411
00:24:58,000 --> 00:24:59,000
Marshall High School.

412
00:24:59,000 --> 00:25:01,000
He was a principal at the time.

413
00:25:01,000 --> 00:25:03,000
And I came back and told him that I wanted a job.

414
00:25:03,000 --> 00:25:06,000
And I was hired that same fall.

415
00:25:06,000 --> 00:25:09,000
At that time, school was started in September.

416
00:25:09,000 --> 00:25:11,000
We got back from Chicago in August.

417
00:25:11,000 --> 00:25:13,000
And I told him that I wanted to work.

418
00:25:13,000 --> 00:25:16,000
And he had me for the September session.

419
00:25:16,000 --> 00:25:19,000
Did you have a divided session then?

420
00:25:19,000 --> 00:25:21,000
No, it was all the same.

421
00:25:21,000 --> 00:25:23,000
We were back on the nine months, got you.

422
00:25:23,000 --> 00:25:24,000
Right.

423
00:25:24,000 --> 00:25:28,000
And I guess it was, no, one nine month, eight months.

424
00:25:28,000 --> 00:25:30,000
Eight months, eight months, eight months.

425
00:25:30,000 --> 00:25:32,000
And where were you teaching then?

426
00:25:32,000 --> 00:25:34,000
Marshall High School right up there on the hill.

427
00:25:34,000 --> 00:25:35,000
Did you say your past?

428
00:25:35,000 --> 00:25:36,000
Oh, I see you were here.

429
00:25:36,000 --> 00:25:37,000
Right here, right up here.

430
00:25:37,000 --> 00:25:39,000
I'm in Tchula, now.

431
00:25:39,000 --> 00:25:43,000
Okay, you moved here with your family.

432
00:25:43,000 --> 00:25:44,000
And...

433
00:25:44,000 --> 00:25:46,000
I had one child at that time.

434
00:25:46,000 --> 00:25:49,000
That's my oldest son, Reginald.

435
00:25:49,000 --> 00:25:51,000
And your husband was farming?

436
00:25:51,000 --> 00:25:52,000
He was farming.

437
00:25:52,000 --> 00:25:59,000
And when he came back, at that time, the movement was just about to get started.

438
00:25:59,000 --> 00:26:02,000
And several people were working around getting the movement started.

439
00:26:02,000 --> 00:26:05,000
So he finally got a job teaching...

440
00:26:05,000 --> 00:26:09,000
And the Civil Rights Movement called it, I believe, was SNCC at the time.

441
00:26:09,000 --> 00:26:10,000
It's NC.

442
00:26:10,000 --> 00:26:11,000
Yeah, it's SNCC.

443
00:26:11,000 --> 00:26:14,000
Okay, so he went there and he worked with them.

444
00:26:14,000 --> 00:26:18,000
And finally got a job with his Child Development Group of Mississippi.

445
00:26:18,000 --> 00:26:19,000
You remember that?

446
00:26:19,000 --> 00:26:21,000
Yeah, we were going to get there.

447
00:26:21,000 --> 00:26:22,000
Okay.

448
00:26:22,000 --> 00:26:28,000
So what I'm saying, he was farming at the same time working with the people to get the movement going.

449
00:26:28,000 --> 00:26:31,000
So he was much more involved with the movement than I was.

450
00:26:31,000 --> 00:26:35,000
As a teacher, why you were limited in some ways?

451
00:26:35,000 --> 00:26:36,000
Very much so.

452
00:26:36,000 --> 00:26:41,000
Very much so because there was a man by the name of John Ball, I believe it was John,

453
00:26:41,000 --> 00:26:48,000
came out of Greenwood and by my husband being actively involved with the Civil Rights Movement,

454
00:26:48,000 --> 00:26:50,000
I guess he thought I would be too.

455
00:26:50,000 --> 00:26:51,000
And he did.

456
00:26:51,000 --> 00:26:54,000
He came by the school and was telling me what was going on.

457
00:26:54,000 --> 00:27:00,000
I didn't know in the bill that I'm standing up there in the hallway just talking to him about what I was going to do and everything.

458
00:27:00,000 --> 00:27:02,000
And the principal came by.

459
00:27:02,000 --> 00:27:05,000
And he didn't say anything, he just passed by.

460
00:27:05,000 --> 00:27:12,000
But in a way, when John Ball left, he told me I was going to eventually lose my job if I didn't let that alone.

461
00:27:12,000 --> 00:27:15,000
Okay, that's I'm glad to hear that.

462
00:27:15,000 --> 00:27:17,000
That's evidence that this thing is going to be.

463
00:27:17,000 --> 00:27:20,000
Yeah, he told me that if I didn't let them...

464
00:27:20,000 --> 00:27:23,000
Now if I didn't let them freedom workers alone, I was going to lose my job.

465
00:27:23,000 --> 00:27:34,000
And naturally, I didn't go bowling with it, but they would come by the house in the afternoon or at night, Saturday afternoon or Saturday night.

466
00:27:34,000 --> 00:27:38,000
They didn't park in the driveway like people had been parking.

467
00:27:38,000 --> 00:27:42,000
So my house was had a driveway around the back.

468
00:27:42,000 --> 00:27:47,000
So they would come and park their cars behind the back of the house so it couldn't have one see them.

469
00:27:47,000 --> 00:27:49,000
So you were very much aware of what was going on?

470
00:27:49,000 --> 00:27:51,000
So during that time...

471
00:27:51,000 --> 00:27:56,000
Yeah, I knew I heard that a number of teachers were sort of behind the scenes doing things.

472
00:27:56,000 --> 00:27:58,000
They couldn't do public.

473
00:27:58,000 --> 00:28:09,000
Right, because many times they wanted lemonade or tea cakes and I would cook and fix some refreshments, you know, while they passing through, they would stop and eat with me and move on or stop and eat.

474
00:28:09,000 --> 00:28:10,000
And you know, we share ideas.

475
00:28:10,000 --> 00:28:15,000
But like you said, behind the scene, I was very active, but all front I was afraid.

476
00:28:15,000 --> 00:28:18,000
Not necessarily afraid, because I really didn't have sense enough to be afraid.

477
00:28:18,000 --> 00:28:26,000
I didn't know what to expect, but I needed to work, so I just kept a low key there.

478
00:28:26,000 --> 00:28:31,000
So what was... you came back to... you came to Chudolain what year then?

479
00:28:31,000 --> 00:28:34,000
Sixty... 63, 62.

480
00:28:34,000 --> 00:28:37,000
Okay, so that was one thing we're really getting underway with SNCC.

481
00:28:37,000 --> 00:28:38,000
Right.

482
00:28:38,000 --> 00:28:48,000
So with the Freedom Vote, that ball, and also the Freedom Summer of the next year when there are about 30 volunteers coming in.

483
00:28:48,000 --> 00:28:49,000
Right.

484
00:28:49,000 --> 00:28:51,000
It's about what you remember about Freedom Summer.

485
00:28:51,000 --> 00:28:58,000
Freedom Summer, for me, was the time when a new man named Abe and somebody came...

486
00:28:58,000 --> 00:28:59,000
Hey, Abe Osheroff, yeah.

487
00:28:59,000 --> 00:29:04,000
Yeah, came to work with the Mileston community.

488
00:29:04,000 --> 00:29:11,000
And at that time they were telling me to build a place to meet because they were meeting an old dilapidated church there in that same area.

489
00:29:11,000 --> 00:29:16,000
So Abe came in and they built that... what we call the Mileston...

490
00:29:16,000 --> 00:29:19,000
Oh, it was a Mileston Community Center.

491
00:29:19,000 --> 00:29:22,000
And that's where we would start meeting.

492
00:29:22,000 --> 00:29:25,000
Now I could go there because it was at home, okay.

493
00:29:25,000 --> 00:29:28,000
But anyway, during that time, there was very...

494
00:29:29,000 --> 00:29:33,000
Quite a few people were working and quite a few people were attending this...

495
00:29:33,000 --> 00:29:35,000
You know, the...

496
00:29:35,000 --> 00:29:42,000
I guess you call it the work session that they were having as to how to do when you get ready to vote and how you conduct yourselves and all of that.

497
00:29:42,000 --> 00:29:45,000
They prepared people to go out and vote.

498
00:29:45,000 --> 00:29:49,000
But now prepare people to register and later to go out and vote.

499
00:29:49,000 --> 00:29:52,000
So you was at Henry Lorenzi, Sue Lorenzi, in the fall of 64.

500
00:29:52,000 --> 00:29:54,000
Right. I remember them, yes.

501
00:29:54,000 --> 00:29:56,000
They were all very well, very well.

502
00:29:56,000 --> 00:30:00,000
Sue Lorenzi was young lady.

503
00:30:00,000 --> 00:30:06,000
Henry was young fellow and Henry told me one thing I never forget.

504
00:30:06,000 --> 00:30:08,000
He said, Ms. Burns, you're going...

505
00:30:08,000 --> 00:30:10,000
No, you don't...

506
00:30:10,000 --> 00:30:11,000
Why did you tip that on that?

507
00:30:11,000 --> 00:30:14,000
Ms. Burns, you think people like you.

508
00:30:14,000 --> 00:30:16,000
And I said, how is that?

509
00:30:16,000 --> 00:30:18,000
He said, you understand fair.

510
00:30:18,000 --> 00:30:20,000
People are not understand fair.

511
00:30:20,000 --> 00:30:22,000
I never would forget that.

512
00:30:24,000 --> 00:30:26,000
Hey, you tell me people are understand fair.

513
00:30:26,000 --> 00:30:28,000
You know, I was understand fair.

514
00:30:28,000 --> 00:30:30,000
People are not understand fair.

515
00:30:30,000 --> 00:30:32,000
And he looked at me just as strange.

516
00:30:32,000 --> 00:30:34,000
I heard Henry's story.

517
00:30:34,000 --> 00:30:37,000
Oh, Henry was something else, not.

518
00:30:37,000 --> 00:30:39,000
He would tell you just what he thought about you though.

519
00:30:39,000 --> 00:30:44,000
But at the same time, he really worked hard to help the people in the community.

520
00:30:44,000 --> 00:30:47,000
I appreciate that too.

521
00:30:47,000 --> 00:30:53,000
So we have the Freedom Summer coming on and the formation of the Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party.

522
00:30:53,000 --> 00:30:55,000
That was your husband involved with all of this?

523
00:30:55,000 --> 00:30:57,000
He was.

524
00:30:57,000 --> 00:31:07,000
He was one of the ones who asked to did the teaching of the registration,

525
00:31:07,000 --> 00:31:11,000
voted to get out and all of that, along with...

526
00:31:11,000 --> 00:31:14,000
I don't know if anyone ever mentioned to you, Reverend Whitaker,

527
00:31:14,000 --> 00:31:15,000
you remember Reverend Whitaker?

528
00:31:15,000 --> 00:31:16,000
Yes.

529
00:31:16,000 --> 00:31:17,000
They all worked together.

530
00:31:17,000 --> 00:31:20,000
Reverend Russell.

531
00:31:20,000 --> 00:31:25,000
And there was a little young lady about a name of Emma Nola Williams,

532
00:31:25,000 --> 00:31:26,000
you remember her?

533
00:31:26,000 --> 00:31:27,000
No.

534
00:31:27,000 --> 00:31:31,000
Emma Nola Williams worked in that class also, Bernie Smangum, right?

535
00:31:31,000 --> 00:31:32,000
Yes, she was a teacher.

536
00:31:32,000 --> 00:31:35,000
Right, she was a teacher too.

537
00:31:35,000 --> 00:31:39,000
But those are the ones who Bernie's was working in.

538
00:31:39,000 --> 00:31:42,000
She came to Boston too, but that was the one who read was...

539
00:31:42,000 --> 00:31:49,000
All of these people, I think, named were standing in the Mileston community except Rev. Arrell Whitaker.

540
00:31:49,000 --> 00:31:53,000
He lived in Tchula, but he was a person who wanted to have a better life,

541
00:31:53,000 --> 00:31:56,000
so he would come down and work with them.

542
00:31:56,000 --> 00:31:59,000
And there was another young man named Marshall.

543
00:31:59,000 --> 00:32:03,000
Marshall was out from the Roosevelt Bank Monologue community.

544
00:32:03,000 --> 00:32:04,000
I believe it was F.D. Marshall.

545
00:32:04,000 --> 00:32:06,000
You remember that name?

546
00:32:06,000 --> 00:32:07,000
Okay.

547
00:32:07,000 --> 00:32:08,000
Anyway, they all worked together.

548
00:32:08,000 --> 00:32:12,000
And that's how the Child Development Group of Mississippi...

549
00:32:12,000 --> 00:32:16,000
Head Start program got started, and they worked with that.

550
00:32:16,000 --> 00:32:21,000
I particularly glad to have you as a teacher here teaching during this time,

551
00:32:21,000 --> 00:32:30,000
because it was in 1965 that a federal court ordered Holmes County to be getting desegregating its all white schools.

552
00:32:30,000 --> 00:32:31,000
Okay.

553
00:32:31,000 --> 00:32:36,000
Talk about that from your perspective in the second year of high school and the parents of the kids.

554
00:32:36,000 --> 00:32:40,000
At that, during the year 65, I was not teaching.

555
00:32:40,000 --> 00:32:41,000
I was pregnant.

556
00:32:41,000 --> 00:32:43,000
You know, during that time, if you were pregnant, you couldn't teach school.

557
00:32:43,000 --> 00:32:48,000
But anyway, my son was going into the first grade, second grade.

558
00:32:48,000 --> 00:32:49,000
I'm not sure.

559
00:32:49,000 --> 00:32:55,000
And he was one of the ones who went to the Tchula Consolidated School,

560
00:32:55,000 --> 00:33:00,000
the Tchula High School, which was a white school in town.

561
00:33:00,000 --> 00:33:08,000
The Tchula who came out of first grade that year went to first grade at that school to integrate it.

562
00:33:08,000 --> 00:33:09,000
Your son was one of those?

563
00:33:09,000 --> 00:33:10,000
My son was one of those.

564
00:33:10,000 --> 00:33:12,000
What was about his experience in your...

565
00:33:12,000 --> 00:33:17,000
Well, now as a parent, we were trying to make life better for everyone.

566
00:33:17,000 --> 00:33:22,000
And, um, it was about a little afraid now, because they went to school,

567
00:33:22,000 --> 00:33:26,000
and I don't know what was a week of money, what have you, but the school burned down.

568
00:33:26,000 --> 00:33:30,000
They burnt the school down when they found out that the black people were coming in.

569
00:33:30,000 --> 00:33:35,000
And the next, after the children didn't get scared and run,

570
00:33:35,000 --> 00:33:38,000
and the parents didn't pull them out, they burned another segment,

571
00:33:38,000 --> 00:33:40,000
another part of the school down.

572
00:33:41,000 --> 00:33:46,000
They was trying to run them out, but my son and that group, they stayed.

573
00:33:46,000 --> 00:33:47,000
And...

574
00:33:47,000 --> 00:33:50,000
Were you working at group of black kids that integrated?

575
00:33:50,000 --> 00:33:53,000
I think was 16 in his first grade class.

576
00:33:53,000 --> 00:33:54,000
I don't know.

577
00:33:54,000 --> 00:33:55,000
Considerable number.

578
00:33:55,000 --> 00:33:56,000
Right, right.

579
00:33:56,000 --> 00:33:57,000
I don't know about the other class.

580
00:33:57,000 --> 00:33:59,000
I just remember the class that my son was in.

581
00:33:59,000 --> 00:34:01,000
I think it was 16 in his class.

582
00:34:01,000 --> 00:34:05,000
And Christopher Epps, you heard of him?

583
00:34:05,000 --> 00:34:06,000
Yeah.

584
00:34:06,000 --> 00:34:08,000
Christopher Epps was my son's classmate.

585
00:34:08,000 --> 00:34:15,000
And Christopher and I was a director of my freshman.

586
00:34:15,000 --> 00:34:17,000
Did he have...

587
00:34:17,000 --> 00:34:20,000
Did he come home when I cried about...

588
00:34:20,000 --> 00:34:25,000
No, no, he never did complain about anything, but his teacher, his teacher was whipping me.

589
00:34:25,000 --> 00:34:27,000
He didn't like getting a whipping at all.

590
00:34:27,000 --> 00:34:28,000
So my son never...

591
00:34:28,000 --> 00:34:30,000
Did you hear any white friends there?

592
00:34:30,000 --> 00:34:31,000
They weren't there, they left.

593
00:34:31,000 --> 00:34:32,000
All the white...

594
00:34:32,000 --> 00:34:35,000
They all left when the blacks got there, they all the whites left.

595
00:34:35,000 --> 00:34:37,000
I see, so it just...

596
00:34:37,000 --> 00:34:39,000
It left it all black.

597
00:34:39,000 --> 00:34:43,000
So that re-saggregation happened there really early this year.

598
00:34:43,000 --> 00:34:44,000
That's right.

599
00:34:44,000 --> 00:34:45,000
And you mean that way ever since?

600
00:34:45,000 --> 00:34:46,000
It's been never way ever since.

601
00:34:46,000 --> 00:34:48,000
So they finally got rid of the...

602
00:34:48,000 --> 00:34:52,000
I think there's one building left and there was a shop building.

603
00:34:52,000 --> 00:34:54,000
The shop building is there now.

604
00:34:54,000 --> 00:34:56,000
But they burned everything else down.

605
00:34:56,000 --> 00:34:57,000
Mm-hmm.

606
00:34:57,000 --> 00:35:00,000
They was determined not to be there with those black children.

607
00:35:00,000 --> 00:35:04,000
They went to Cruger-Tchula Academy and developed a Cruger-Tchula Academy Tchula Academy.

608
00:35:04,000 --> 00:35:05,000
Okay, so...

609
00:35:05,000 --> 00:35:11,000
I don't know what it was called before then, but later on it turned out to be the Cruger-Tchula Academy Tchula Academy.

610
00:35:11,000 --> 00:35:15,000
So here, like we grew up, we were in Jackson at the time.

611
00:35:15,000 --> 00:35:16,000
Okay.

612
00:35:16,000 --> 00:35:22,000
There was integration of schools and for a while you had black and white kids going to school together

613
00:35:22,000 --> 00:35:23,000
and then the whites would pull out.

614
00:35:23,000 --> 00:35:25,000
But this happened just practically overnight?

615
00:35:25,000 --> 00:35:26,000
It did, it did here.

616
00:35:26,000 --> 00:35:29,000
Well, when they found out that the blacks...

617
00:35:29,000 --> 00:35:38,000
The same black group of people from Austin who are not afraid to go register vote had children.

618
00:35:38,000 --> 00:35:45,000
All of those children went together to integrate the Tchula Consolidated School.

619
00:35:45,000 --> 00:35:51,000
And when they found out that that's what was going on, they just stopped burning the plays down.

620
00:35:51,000 --> 00:35:52,000
No.

621
00:35:52,000 --> 00:35:53,000
Okay.

622
00:35:53,000 --> 00:35:55,000
And then they built the segregation of the Academy.

623
00:35:55,000 --> 00:35:56,000
Right.

624
00:35:56,000 --> 00:35:57,000
Shortly thereafter.

625
00:35:57,000 --> 00:35:58,000
After that, right.

626
00:35:58,000 --> 00:36:02,000
So then you came back to school to teach in 1966?

627
00:36:02,000 --> 00:36:03,000
I came back in 1967.

628
00:36:03,000 --> 00:36:05,000
I was out two years ago.

629
00:36:05,000 --> 00:36:07,000
So talk about that experience.

630
00:36:07,000 --> 00:36:10,000
That was a pleasant experience for me.

631
00:36:10,000 --> 00:36:12,000
I had no problem of coming back to school.

632
00:36:12,000 --> 00:36:14,000
I had no problem coming back to school.

633
00:36:14,000 --> 00:36:18,000
Not the facility, not the setup that was there.

634
00:36:18,000 --> 00:36:25,000
It wasn't smooth sailing, but it was better than I was first introduced to.

635
00:36:25,000 --> 00:36:28,000
What kind of opportunities were there for your students?

636
00:36:28,000 --> 00:36:32,000
And many of them got to go on to college or junior college?

637
00:36:32,000 --> 00:36:35,000
Many went on to college.

638
00:36:35,000 --> 00:36:37,000
And some did go to junior college.

639
00:36:37,000 --> 00:36:41,000
But at that time, at home, right, it was over then.

640
00:36:41,000 --> 00:36:44,000
They would go right on to college.

641
00:36:44,000 --> 00:36:48,000
Mississippi Valley State, Jackson State and all core.

642
00:36:48,000 --> 00:36:50,000
Still going into a predominantly black area.

643
00:36:50,000 --> 00:36:52,000
That's all they were used to.

644
00:36:52,000 --> 00:36:57,000
And by that time, really, they were the one who recruited those students who wanted to come.

645
00:36:57,000 --> 00:37:02,000
It was recently that the white institution came to recruit the black children.

646
00:37:02,000 --> 00:37:03,000
When was...

647
00:37:03,000 --> 00:37:05,000
Did you recall when the first...

648
00:37:05,000 --> 00:37:09,000
Your high school students went to Ole Miss or one of the white schools?

649
00:37:09,000 --> 00:37:10,000
Oh, no.

650
00:37:10,000 --> 00:37:12,000
That was very recently.

651
00:37:12,000 --> 00:37:13,000
Oh, no.

652
00:37:13,000 --> 00:37:16,000
The university saved, of course, in 1962.

653
00:37:16,000 --> 00:37:17,000
And there were a handful.

654
00:37:17,000 --> 00:37:20,000
And now there are more black students there than there are two blue.

655
00:37:21,000 --> 00:37:26,000
Because we had a student who finished about four years, maybe five years ago.

656
00:37:26,000 --> 00:37:28,000
And he was...

657
00:37:28,000 --> 00:37:31,000
I mean, he enrolled at Ole Miss and he was accepted.

658
00:37:31,000 --> 00:37:36,000
I don't know what you heard of Antoine Patrick, the Patrick down on my cellar.

659
00:37:36,000 --> 00:37:40,000
He finished at Ole Miss, returning.

660
00:37:40,000 --> 00:37:43,000
So, that's still about it.

661
00:37:43,000 --> 00:37:45,000
Oh, you know, let me get to you.

662
00:37:45,000 --> 00:37:46,000
Straight about 80.

663
00:37:46,000 --> 00:37:48,000
No, almost 80.

664
00:37:48,000 --> 00:37:49,000
92.

665
00:37:49,000 --> 00:37:51,000
93, something like that.

666
00:37:51,000 --> 00:37:58,000
So, compared to that with now, are there more kids going to college now than back then or fewer?

667
00:37:58,000 --> 00:38:00,000
Are they going to different places?

668
00:38:00,000 --> 00:38:04,000
Back then, there were few.

669
00:38:04,000 --> 00:38:07,000
And the problem then was because of finance.

670
00:38:07,000 --> 00:38:12,000
They didn't have grants and loans and fellowships and scholarships like they have now.

671
00:38:12,000 --> 00:38:17,000
And that made the number few because parents were not able to send them off to school.

672
00:38:17,000 --> 00:38:23,000
But now, you have more students, I think, going to school.

673
00:38:23,000 --> 00:38:24,000
But I really want to believe it.

674
00:38:24,000 --> 00:38:25,000
I hope I'm wrong.

675
00:38:25,000 --> 00:38:27,000
That they go in for the wrong reason.

676
00:38:27,000 --> 00:38:33,000
Because I see them going to school and all of a sudden they get the grant money and go buy a car.

677
00:38:33,000 --> 00:38:36,000
And they drop out of school.

678
00:38:36,000 --> 00:38:40,000
Now, compared to what happened then after what's going on now,

679
00:38:40,000 --> 00:38:44,000
the majority of the students went to school then for a good purpose.

680
00:38:44,000 --> 00:38:46,000
They had a reason for going.

681
00:38:46,000 --> 00:38:50,000
But now they're trying to be the system.

682
00:38:50,000 --> 00:38:52,000
And that's Bay.

683
00:38:52,000 --> 00:38:54,000
But I see a lot of that in my community.

684
00:38:54,000 --> 00:38:59,000
I hear quite a bit of that too.

685
00:38:59,000 --> 00:39:03,000
I hear some of the teachers get their degrees that way online.

686
00:39:03,000 --> 00:39:04,000
I think it's Bay.

687
00:39:04,000 --> 00:39:11,000
I think it's Robin, I was students of the very necessity of being trained by people who have been trained.

688
00:39:11,000 --> 00:39:18,000
Now, believe it or not, those people who get those degrees online, that's compared to how I got in mind.

689
00:39:18,000 --> 00:39:22,000
I just don't see them being as concerned as that was.

690
00:39:22,000 --> 00:39:26,000
And I'm working right along there with them now.

691
00:39:26,000 --> 00:39:28,000
Well, this is certainly up.

692
00:39:28,000 --> 00:39:39,000
And you read recently where these are places where students have gotten college loans and the online universities have taken them and they drop out rates just over a while.

693
00:39:39,000 --> 00:39:40,000
It is. It is.

694
00:39:40,000 --> 00:39:43,000
Equipment and poach out.

695
00:39:43,000 --> 00:39:48,000
Well, I want to turn to something out that is a very interesting thing.

696
00:39:48,000 --> 00:39:50,000
And that is state that election to win.

697
00:39:50,000 --> 00:39:54,000
Tell us why you ran for the school board and about that campaign.

698
00:39:54,000 --> 00:39:58,000
Was that your first venture and electoral politics?

699
00:39:58,000 --> 00:40:00,000
It was.

700
00:40:00,000 --> 00:40:04,000
I ran because, like I said, keeping up with the movement now.

701
00:40:04,000 --> 00:40:09,000
And I knew the situation when it comes to education because I'd been a parent, was a teacher.

702
00:40:09,000 --> 00:40:12,000
And I said, well, let me do something to make it better.

703
00:40:12,000 --> 00:40:15,000
If I was a board member, I could do something about the problem that I was facing.

704
00:40:15,000 --> 00:40:17,000
So I ran and I was elected.

705
00:40:17,000 --> 00:40:23,000
I stayed there until, um, seventy, seventy, seventy five or seventy six.

706
00:40:23,000 --> 00:40:25,000
Did you campaign for the election?

707
00:40:25,000 --> 00:40:28,000
I did. I did. I campaign hard.

708
00:40:28,000 --> 00:40:31,000
Well, you got knock on doors for you.

709
00:40:31,000 --> 00:40:34,000
Um, not really knock on doors per se.

710
00:40:34,000 --> 00:40:39,000
Just out there in the churches and the communities letting people know that I was out there.

711
00:40:39,000 --> 00:40:43,000
Interesting making a better life and education for the children and the teachers.

712
00:40:43,000 --> 00:40:45,000
And everybody went for it.

713
00:40:45,000 --> 00:40:48,000
Campaign and during that time is not like campaigning now.

714
00:40:48,000 --> 00:40:54,000
If you had a cause or reason to go, they will support you because they wanted things to be better.

715
00:40:54,000 --> 00:40:57,000
And that's the way it went for me.

716
00:40:57,000 --> 00:41:00,000
Now, you were one against the white candidate.

717
00:41:00,000 --> 00:41:05,000
Well, unfortunately, his name was not on the ballot.

718
00:41:05,000 --> 00:41:06,000
Let me go back.

719
00:41:06,000 --> 00:41:12,000
When I stood out to run, he was alive and well.

720
00:41:12,000 --> 00:41:20,000
I guess by the first time the black person opposed him, he just couldn't take it.

721
00:41:20,000 --> 00:41:25,000
He died the night before the election or two nights before the election.

722
00:41:25,000 --> 00:41:28,000
I said, when I started out, he was alive and well.

723
00:41:28,000 --> 00:41:30,000
But he just couldn't make it.

724
00:41:30,000 --> 00:41:34,000
Martin Smith. I never forget it down there.

725
00:41:34,000 --> 00:41:37,000
So by now, the schools are overwhelming.

726
00:41:37,000 --> 00:41:43,000
They are totally black and yet they're still having white infositions of power.

727
00:41:43,000 --> 00:41:48,000
They still had a white superintendent and white board members, white attorney, white everything.

728
00:41:48,000 --> 00:41:53,000
When I won the election, I think I was the second black person on the board.

729
00:41:53,000 --> 00:41:54,000
Others all white.

730
00:41:54,000 --> 00:42:03,000
There was a leader on there already by the name of Dr. Arenia C. Mallory, the Saints Industrial School name for her.

731
00:42:03,000 --> 00:42:04,000
Dr. Arenia C. Mallory.

732
00:42:04,000 --> 00:42:07,000
She was on the board.

733
00:42:07,000 --> 00:42:11,000
Dr. Arenia C. Mallory was okay.

734
00:42:11,000 --> 00:42:17,000
She just, oh, how can I describe him?

735
00:42:17,000 --> 00:42:22,000
She saw things the way the white folks saw things.

736
00:42:22,000 --> 00:42:25,000
She told me one day right across the table from me.

737
00:42:25,000 --> 00:42:29,000
You're sitting up here, you're trying to get everything, white folks, not everything,

738
00:42:29,000 --> 00:42:34,000
not black folks, they're going to make you alive and stalkers of the community out a while.

739
00:42:34,000 --> 00:42:36,000
I just couldn't believe that.

740
00:42:36,000 --> 00:42:41,000
Because everything that teachers and the parents were asked for, I didn't have any better sense.

741
00:42:41,000 --> 00:42:44,000
I went and told them to sit and turn to the board what we wanted.

742
00:42:44,000 --> 00:42:48,000
And she thought there was true aggressive, I guess, because she didn't ask for anything.

743
00:42:48,000 --> 00:42:49,000
She didn't bother about anything.

744
00:42:49,000 --> 00:42:51,000
Everything was okay for her.

745
00:42:51,000 --> 00:42:56,000
But she was on the board, but she had the academy going.

746
00:42:56,000 --> 00:42:59,000
There was a college, anyone in the academy.

747
00:42:59,000 --> 00:43:06,000
Why do I have heard a lot about her that she was very opinionated and that she was doing things

748
00:43:06,000 --> 00:43:08,000
and that was the way to do it?

749
00:43:08,000 --> 00:43:11,000
So you were on the board with her, how many were on the school board?

750
00:43:11,000 --> 00:43:12,000
Five.

751
00:43:12,000 --> 00:43:14,000
And there were three whites?

752
00:43:14,000 --> 00:43:15,000
Three whites and two blacks.

753
00:43:15,000 --> 00:43:20,000
Talk about what issues you deal with in the school board during the time you were with her.

754
00:43:20,000 --> 00:43:25,000
We deal with the issues of staff and mostly.

755
00:43:25,000 --> 00:43:26,000
Funding.

756
00:43:26,000 --> 00:43:34,000
And we end up dealing with building.

757
00:43:34,000 --> 00:43:37,000
Teacher shortage, not enough teachers.

758
00:43:37,000 --> 00:43:40,000
Poor curriculum structure.

759
00:43:40,000 --> 00:43:43,000
Just everything that we deal with now.

760
00:43:43,000 --> 00:43:47,000
Now in the school, the white's bull are still white's teaching in the school.

761
00:43:47,000 --> 00:43:49,000
Yes, so we got white steel teaching.

762
00:43:49,000 --> 00:43:53,000
I mean, back then, some stayed, some went with the...

763
00:43:53,000 --> 00:43:56,000
All of them left.

764
00:43:56,000 --> 00:43:58,000
All of them left.

765
00:43:58,000 --> 00:44:01,000
The children left and the teachers left.

766
00:44:01,000 --> 00:44:06,000
But the academies began to phase out.

767
00:44:06,000 --> 00:44:09,000
All the academies.

768
00:44:09,000 --> 00:44:12,000
We got one, I think, in homes, countless, and likes it to them.

769
00:44:12,000 --> 00:44:15,000
So the teachers didn't have anything to do.

770
00:44:15,000 --> 00:44:18,000
You understand what I'm coming from now?

771
00:44:18,000 --> 00:44:21,000
So where did the white school and the academies phase out?

772
00:44:21,000 --> 00:44:23,000
They went to the other public school.

773
00:44:23,000 --> 00:44:25,000
They didn't come back to the homes kind of now.

774
00:44:25,000 --> 00:44:27,000
They went to Greenwood or...

775
00:44:27,000 --> 00:44:32,000
They left the education system all together.

776
00:44:32,000 --> 00:44:35,000
And their families moved or did they just pay to go to the other...

777
00:44:35,000 --> 00:44:36,000
They paid to go.

778
00:44:36,000 --> 00:44:40,000
But in Durant, they set up the separate school district in Durant.

779
00:44:40,000 --> 00:44:46,000
And that accommodated the white because the white's in this era who couldn't afford to pay for the academies,

780
00:44:46,000 --> 00:44:48,000
they went to the Durant school.

781
00:44:48,000 --> 00:44:50,000
They stayed in operation.

782
00:44:50,000 --> 00:44:56,000
But eventually all of the whites left there because it was in flux with black students.

783
00:44:56,000 --> 00:45:02,000
So all the white teachers left but on the school board, you hired whites to teach in the schools here?

784
00:45:02,000 --> 00:45:03,000
Yes.

785
00:45:03,000 --> 00:45:05,000
These were younger people.

786
00:45:05,000 --> 00:45:07,000
Younger people with different kind of experiences.

787
00:45:07,000 --> 00:45:09,000
Did they work out, okay?

788
00:45:09,000 --> 00:45:10,000
They did.

789
00:45:10,000 --> 00:45:12,000
It worked out well.

790
00:45:12,000 --> 00:45:15,000
So what was the racial makeup of when you...

791
00:45:15,000 --> 00:45:18,000
You left the board in 1976.

792
00:45:18,000 --> 00:45:19,000
1976, right?

793
00:45:19,000 --> 00:45:21,000
What was the racial makeup of the faculty?

794
00:45:21,000 --> 00:45:23,000
Generally, I know you don't...

795
00:45:23,000 --> 00:45:24,000
Black and white?

796
00:45:24,000 --> 00:45:25,000
Yeah.

797
00:45:25,000 --> 00:45:27,000
We probably had...

798
00:45:27,000 --> 00:45:33,000
At the most, probably two whites in each school.

799
00:45:33,000 --> 00:45:41,000
At the most, it was not necessarily a white teacher, but a white was there.

800
00:45:41,000 --> 00:45:45,000
And what did you have in your first black superintendent?

801
00:45:45,000 --> 00:45:51,000
The black superintendent came along with the election of William Dean.

802
00:45:51,000 --> 00:45:53,000
I'm not sure what he was.

803
00:45:53,000 --> 00:45:55,000
I'm not good with dates like that.

804
00:45:55,000 --> 00:45:57,000
William Dean.

805
00:45:57,000 --> 00:45:58,000
Who had him?

806
00:45:58,000 --> 00:46:02,000
Was it in the 80s or 90s or more recently?

807
00:46:02,000 --> 00:46:03,000
Late 80s.

808
00:46:03,000 --> 00:46:04,000
Late 80s.

809
00:46:04,000 --> 00:46:06,000
So you had a white superintendent up until then?

810
00:46:06,000 --> 00:46:08,000
Right, up until then.

811
00:46:08,000 --> 00:46:15,000
Before we let you go, there's something that I'm really interested in having you.

812
00:46:15,000 --> 00:46:19,000
And ask back to your professional career that I want you to talk about.

813
00:46:19,000 --> 00:46:20,000
Okay.

814
00:46:20,000 --> 00:46:31,000
Now that way, as you were an actor participant in the research conducted on the Black family and Holmes County by University of Illinois professor of Dr. Demitri Shimkin and his associates.

815
00:46:31,000 --> 00:46:39,000
And the result was a highly praised book, The Extended Family and Black Societies published in 1968.

816
00:46:39,000 --> 00:46:42,000
Tell us about that project and your role in it.

817
00:46:42,000 --> 00:46:44,000
That project grew out of the...

818
00:46:44,000 --> 00:46:47,000
Like I said, the Mileston Cooperative.

819
00:46:47,000 --> 00:46:54,000
There was a Mileston Cooperative that helped to initiate the Holmes County Health Research Program.

820
00:46:54,000 --> 00:47:02,000
From the Holmes County Health Research Program, we went through house to house, door to door, studying students, studying people.

821
00:47:02,000 --> 00:47:08,000
And we found that there were people with more hypertension problems than we had realized.

822
00:47:08,000 --> 00:47:10,000
We didn't know what to expect.

823
00:47:10,000 --> 00:47:16,000
And then we discovered that there were a child as young as six years old suffering from hypertension.

824
00:47:16,000 --> 00:47:17,000
I never would forget that.

825
00:47:17,000 --> 00:47:18,000
That was hard to believe.

826
00:47:18,000 --> 00:47:21,000
Because I thought there was an old person disease.

827
00:47:21,000 --> 00:47:22,000
Yeah.

828
00:47:22,000 --> 00:47:24,000
And we had a child in there with hypertension.

829
00:47:24,000 --> 00:47:33,000
That was a situation where we all were meet together and they were going to survey families, health condition.

830
00:47:33,000 --> 00:47:38,000
And with the health condition, they also proved into the economic condition.

831
00:47:38,000 --> 00:47:45,000
And all of that, they would go around to see if you have bathrooms and running water and all that kind of stuff.

832
00:47:45,000 --> 00:47:56,000
It was a time where the Holmes County Health Research was trying to find out what did people have in Holmes County, help-wise.

833
00:47:56,000 --> 00:47:59,000
And it worked out well with Dr. Demitri Shimkin and...

834
00:47:59,000 --> 00:48:01,000
Well, I can't call other names.

835
00:48:01,000 --> 00:48:03,000
What was your...

836
00:48:03,000 --> 00:48:06,000
My role was secretary of the Holmes County.

837
00:48:06,000 --> 00:48:12,000
Now my role was secretary for the Mileston Cooperative, which funded the Holmes County Health Research Program.

838
00:48:12,000 --> 00:48:17,000
And I was just a go-between between the University of Illinois and the Holmes County people.

839
00:48:17,000 --> 00:48:22,000
So I guess I was just all around finding out what was going on.

840
00:48:22,000 --> 00:48:27,000
And I would communicate with Dr. Demitri Shimkin as to what we needed to do.

841
00:48:27,000 --> 00:48:31,000
And I would feed it to the people in the Holmes County Health Research Program, other cooperation.

842
00:48:31,000 --> 00:48:33,000
And they would care out those activities.

843
00:48:33,000 --> 00:48:34,000
Okay.

844
00:48:34,000 --> 00:48:36,000
What things did you recommend?

845
00:48:36,000 --> 00:48:39,000
Recommended that we needed to look at economic development.

846
00:48:39,000 --> 00:48:42,000
And you know, you needed more money within the county.

847
00:48:42,000 --> 00:48:48,000
And eventually there was a program developed called Robert F. Kennedy Economic Development.

848
00:48:48,000 --> 00:48:51,000
And rather than the clock, it was the chairperson of that.

849
00:48:51,000 --> 00:48:56,000
The things that Dr. Demitri Shimkin would tell us that we needed, I would share with the community people.

850
00:48:56,000 --> 00:49:00,000
And they would, you know, come up with a way of developing them.

851
00:49:00,000 --> 00:49:06,000
And from that also now, we will talk about lunches in the school.

852
00:49:06,000 --> 00:49:13,000
Holmes County Health Research Program looked at what was going on into the school, especially when the chair got to be up to 30 degrees.

853
00:49:13,000 --> 00:49:18,000
And that's why we decided to have lunches for the children, the breakfast.

854
00:49:18,000 --> 00:49:20,000
We started with the breakfast called the lunch program.

855
00:49:20,000 --> 00:49:22,000
Do you have a health care that you have a component there?

856
00:49:22,000 --> 00:49:24,000
In the school system?

857
00:49:24,000 --> 00:49:31,000
Well, in the study, when you said you studied health care, were there any solutions proposed or programs initiated?

858
00:49:31,000 --> 00:49:34,000
Of course you had the community health centers coming in.

859
00:49:34,000 --> 00:49:47,000
Well, with Dr. Demitri Shimkin, and I can't think of this other doctor's name, but anyway, he came by and we developed a health facility, something like a clinic.

860
00:49:47,000 --> 00:49:55,000
And from that clinic, you know, we were able to study and work with some of those people who had a problem.

861
00:49:55,000 --> 00:50:01,000
Now, do you eradicate them now? We studied and work with them in order that they would have a better health.

862
00:50:01,000 --> 00:50:04,000
You also studied black migration.

863
00:50:04,000 --> 00:50:07,000
Yes, we did. What were you finding, sir?

864
00:50:07,000 --> 00:50:11,000
The population shift within the county.

865
00:50:11,000 --> 00:50:15,000
And one time there were plantations all around.

866
00:50:15,000 --> 00:50:24,000
And the population shift because in the cities like Lexington and Pickens and Goodman and Durant, they built apartments.

867
00:50:24,000 --> 00:50:26,000
They called them, I guess, the apartment.

868
00:50:26,000 --> 00:50:32,000
And the people on the plantation came into the city and they left nothing out in the country.

869
00:50:32,000 --> 00:50:35,000
So they migrated to the city.

870
00:50:35,000 --> 00:50:37,000
By that sharecropping was...

871
00:50:37,000 --> 00:50:40,000
Dwellen, Dwellen, Fas.

872
00:50:40,000 --> 00:50:46,000
What about Didin Gideon with Northern migration and all you talked about members of your own family leaving?

873
00:50:46,000 --> 00:50:49,000
Was that something that you studied?

874
00:50:49,000 --> 00:51:01,000
I studied that, but we noticed that it was going on because, like I said, people in the community, they left and went to Chicago for a better job.

875
00:51:01,000 --> 00:51:06,000
Whether it was not with the Wisconsin, Peoria and Oil.

876
00:51:06,000 --> 00:51:11,000
Believe it or not, the majority of the people who left here settling some of those areas.

877
00:51:11,000 --> 00:51:15,000
Chicago, Peoria, Wisconsin, and like that.

878
00:51:15,000 --> 00:51:21,000
Did you studied all the impact of the civil rights movement on families?

879
00:51:21,000 --> 00:51:23,000
I cannot recall.

880
00:51:23,000 --> 00:51:31,000
Obviously, we could see that things were changing and things were getting better for them because of the civil rights movement.

881
00:51:31,000 --> 00:51:39,000
Many people never thought that they were in the shape that they were in until they looked at by those civil rights workers.

882
00:51:39,000 --> 00:51:42,000
It opened your eyes to a whole lot of things.

883
00:51:42,000 --> 00:51:51,000
I guess we were poor and we didn't know we were poor until someone told us we were poor.

884
00:51:51,000 --> 00:51:56,000
Talk to us a little bit about your career over the last 35 years.

885
00:51:56,000 --> 00:52:00,000
We've taken it up to the end (of my time) on the school board.

886
00:52:00,000 --> 00:52:07,000
After the school board, while on the school board, I worked at (Mississippi) Valley, English and Literature.

887
00:52:07,000 --> 00:52:10,000
I stayed into 76.

888
00:52:10,000 --> 00:52:14,000
Came back into the public schools of Holmes County.

889
00:52:14,000 --> 00:52:19,000
I've been working in the public schools system at Holmes County ever since then.

890
00:52:19,000 --> 00:52:21,000
Pretty good.

891
00:52:21,000 --> 00:52:24,000
What are you still teaching now?

892
00:52:24,000 --> 00:52:27,000
I'm teaching three hours a day part time.

893
00:52:27,000 --> 00:52:30,000
I retired in 2006.

894
00:52:30,000 --> 00:52:34,000
They told me then they was looking for someone to replace me in my foreign language department.

895
00:52:34,000 --> 00:52:36,000
I teach French.

896
00:52:36,000 --> 00:52:39,000
Here it is 2012, 2013.

897
00:52:39,000 --> 00:52:41,000
Then I'm found a person here.

898
00:52:41,000 --> 00:52:43,000
So when did you pick up French?

899
00:52:43,000 --> 00:52:48,000
I did French when I was a student at (Mississippi) Valley.

900
00:52:48,000 --> 00:52:54,000
Being on the school board, you just about know what's coming down the pipe.

901
00:52:54,000 --> 00:53:01,000
We were trying to revamp our curriculum, make it better.

902
00:53:01,000 --> 00:53:05,000
I had a chance to look at the curriculum from the state.

903
00:53:05,000 --> 00:53:12,000
I always tried to compare what our district was doing as to what the state had done or what the state had to offer.

904
00:53:12,000 --> 00:53:15,000
I saw that foreign language was coming into the state.

905
00:53:15,000 --> 00:53:21,000
It was mandated that each child who goes into a state institution had to have a foreign language.

906
00:53:21,000 --> 00:53:25,000
So I said, oh, no, I can't express more of my foreign language.

907
00:53:25,000 --> 00:53:28,000
I went back to school and got me some French.

908
00:53:28,000 --> 00:53:29,000
Where did you go?

909
00:53:29,000 --> 00:53:30,000
I went to (Mississippi) Valley.

910
00:53:30,000 --> 00:53:32,000
I was telling a cheer about it.

911
00:53:32,000 --> 00:53:34,000
When you went to every school in the state, didn't it?

912
00:53:34,000 --> 00:53:37,000
I went to (Mississippi) State, (no) Delta State.

913
00:53:37,000 --> 00:53:39,000
So you got certified?

914
00:53:39,000 --> 00:53:40,000
Right.

915
00:53:40,000 --> 00:53:42,000
I was doing this for the principal.

916
00:53:42,000 --> 00:53:44,000
I would go every summer.

917
00:53:44,000 --> 00:53:46,000
Nothing to do doing this summer.

918
00:53:46,000 --> 00:53:48,000
You know, teachers don't have anything to do.

919
00:53:48,000 --> 00:53:51,000
I have a job in education in school.

920
00:53:51,000 --> 00:53:54,000
And I'm still there with it.

921
00:53:54,000 --> 00:53:55,000
And I love my job.

922
00:53:55,000 --> 00:53:56,000
I really do.

923
00:53:56,000 --> 00:53:57,000
It's something I enjoy doing.

924
00:53:57,000 --> 00:53:59,000
And I don't consider the job.

925
00:53:59,000 --> 00:54:00,000
No, I don't.

926
00:54:00,000 --> 00:54:02,000
Because I feel like it.

927
00:54:02,000 --> 00:54:03,000
But I feel like going every day.

928
00:54:03,000 --> 00:54:04,000
God has been good to me.

929
00:54:04,000 --> 00:54:06,000
So I get up and go to work every day.

930
00:54:06,000 --> 00:54:08,000
And I have fun with my job.

931
00:54:08,000 --> 00:54:11,000
Well, I just want to thank you very much for your service.

932
00:54:11,000 --> 00:54:12,000
Just one thing here.

933
00:54:12,000 --> 00:54:15,000
From that to the Freedom Summer.

934
00:54:15,000 --> 00:54:18,000
It was my work and I worked long.

935
00:54:18,000 --> 00:54:19,000
Reporter.

936
00:54:19,000 --> 00:54:20,000
Work long?

937
00:54:20,000 --> 00:54:21,000
No.

938
00:54:21,000 --> 00:54:22,000
Okay.

939
00:54:22,000 --> 00:54:26,000
Now, he may have been up to here, but there were so many of them.

940
00:54:26,000 --> 00:54:28,000
And they were spaced out in the county.

941
00:54:28,000 --> 00:54:32,000
All of them did not come to the Mileston community.

942
00:54:32,000 --> 00:54:35,000
So he may have been here in home's county, but I didn't make that name.

943
00:54:35,000 --> 00:54:36,000
Okay.

944
00:54:36,000 --> 00:54:40,000
I think we're off to take now with the director of banks again.

945
00:54:40,000 --> 00:54:42,000
You know you're welcome.

946
00:54:42,000 --> 00:54:45,000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress

947
00:54:45,000 --> 00:54:51,000
and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.
